{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622279"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:01:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:01:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16794"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16794"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.62,0.1,0.14,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9485"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76703"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9485"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16794"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62195"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5170"},{"type":"tags","id":"5172"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"},{"type":"tags","id":"11211"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22417"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22509"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76703"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECalcitonin gene-related peptide (CGRP) is a neuropeptide that causes cerebral arterial dilation as well as exerting pro-inflammatory effects. It is thought to be involved in pain modulation. Medications that target CGRP have been developed for migraine treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of CGRP antagonists?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sequesters CGRP","Blocks CGRP binding to its receptor","Binds and inactivates CGRP","Decrease CGRP synthesis","Increases CGRP receptor expression"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECGRP antagonists function through \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking CGRP binding to its receptor\u003C/strong\u003E. This competitive inhibition at the receptor site prevents CGRP from initiating its downstream effects of vasodilation and neurogenic inflammation in the brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other proposed mechanisms are incorrect because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESequesters CGRP\u003C/strong\u003E - this would reduce available CGRP, a mechanism of action of some monoclonal antibodies that target the CGRP signalling pathway. This is not the MOA of CGRP antagonists. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinds and inactivates CGRP\u003C/strong\u003E - Antagonists do not chemically modify or inactivate CGRP molecules. Monoclonal antibodies against CGRP have been developed as an alternative method of targeting the CGRP signalling pathway. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecrease CGRP synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - These medications do not affect the production of CGRP\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases CGRP receptor expression\u003C/strong\u003E - This would provide more binding sites for CGRP and potentially amplify its effects\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy preventing CGRP from activating its receptor, CGRP antagonists represent one type of medication class targeting the CGRP pathway to interrupt the cascade of events that leads to migraine symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Calcitonin gene-related peptide (CGRP) is a potent vasodilator involved in migraine pathophysiology.","Calcitonin gene-related peptide (CGRP) antagonists work by blocking the binding of CGRP to its receptor, preventing vasodilation and neurogenic inflammation.","CGRP antagonists are effective for both acute treatment and prevention of migraine headaches."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Mohanty D, Lippmann S. CGRP Inhibitors for Migraine. Innov Clin Neurosci. 2020;17(4-6):39-40."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62195"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16794"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62195"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T11:52:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T11:53:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9485"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76703"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"",